E-mail	Re: my thought on right wrong
by Steerpike on Tue Jan 18, 2011 1:37 pm	([msg=52384]see Re: my thought on right wrong[/msg])
I wouldn't be surprised if morals evolved as a survival mechanism. Humans are social creatures and depend on each other for survival. If we did anything to hurt the chances of survival of the community (murder) or incur the anger of the community (stealing), then it would hurt our own chances of survival, either by hindering the survival of the community (which we depend on) or by the community shunning the individual (and the individual will lose a 'tool' of survival). Laws came about to as 'codified morals' that protect the community at the loss of the individual's freedom. People tend to obey the law because they think it benefits them more to obey the law than not to. With that said, if you think breaking the law is more beneficial to you, then there's nothing stopping you. The law only has as much power over the choices you make as you let it. The law may provide consequences for you choice, but it doesn't stop you from making that choice.
